Comment: This is wrong. URL.getFile() *does not* convert a URL to a file name.  It merely returns the path and query portions of the URL.  (The name ‘getFile’ is due to the nature of URLs back when Java 1.0 was released.)  If the original file name contains spaces or any other characters which are illegal in URLs, the result will not be an existing file name.  Also, when running from a .jar file, it’s impossible to convert a resource URL to a file.

Thanks, this was super helpful! One numeric improvement (to avoid catastrophic cancelation) is to sum values after subtracting to get newMeans, i.e.
``` 
cOldMean = c * oldMean
newMean = oldMean + sum_i (new_value[i] - cOldMean) / newCount
```
(in particular, we don't use ```s```)
